# Modern Graphics in GTK 4 (GSK-first)

* Override `vfunc_snapshot(snapshot)` to build render nodes.
* Use `snapshot.append_texture()` (and friends) for GPU-backed drawing.
* Use `snapshot.append_scaled_texture()` (GTK ≥ 4.10) for filter-controlled scaling.
* Prefer **clip + translate** for sprite sheets (zero-copy).
* Avoid CPU pixel copies unless necessary.

**Sprite Sheet Example**

```typescript
vfunc_snapshot(snapshot: Gtk.Snapshot): void {
  const tw = this.tileWidth, th = this.tileHeight;
  const sx = this.tileX * tw, sy = this.tileY * th;

  snapshot.push_clip(new Graphene.Rect({ x: 0, y: 0, width: tw, height: th }));
  snapshot.save();
  snapshot.translate(new Graphene.Point({ x: -sx, y: -sy }));
  snapshot.append_texture(this.texture, new Graphene.Rect({
    x: 0, y: 0,
    width: this.texture.get_width(),
    height: this.texture.get_height()
  }));
  snapshot.restore();
  snapshot.pop();
}
```

**Sub-Texture Extraction (expensive)**

```typescript
function sliceTexture(sheet: Gdk.Texture, sx: number, sy: number, sw: number, sh: number): Gdk.MemoryTexture {
  const W = sheet.get_width();
  const stride = W * 4;
  const src = new Uint8Array(stride * sheet.get_height());
  sheet.download(src);

  const outStride = sw * 4;
  const out = new Uint8Array(outStride * sh);
  for (let r = 0; r < sh; r++) {
    const s0 = (sy + r) * stride + sx * 4;
    out.set(src.subarray(s0, s0 + outStride), r * outStride);
  }
  return Gdk.MemoryTexture.new(sw, sh, Gdk.MemoryFormat.ARGB8888, GLib.Bytes.new(out), outStride);
}
```

# Widget Lifecycle & Memory Management

* **NEVER use `::destroy`** in GTK4.
* **NEVER call `destroy()`** manually — remove via parent (`parent.remove(child)`).
* Trust refcounting & GJS GC.

### Lifecycle Methods

* `vfunc_map` / `vfunc_unmap` — start/stop timeouts, connect/disconnect signals tied to visibility.
* `vfunc_unroot` — cleanup when removed from hierarchy (disconnect global listeners, drop external refs).
* `vfunc_dispose` — break external references only; no heavy JS.
* `vfunc_finalize` — last-chance cleanup (rare in GJS).

### GJS Safety

* Don’t run JS callbacks in `dispose`/`finalize`.
* Manage signals in `map/unmap`.
* Avoid `run_dispose()`.
* Beware closures capturing widgets (disconnect/clear in `unmap`/`unroot`).

# **GC & VFunc Safety (GJS) — Fix for “Attempting to run a JS callback during GC … get\_flags()”**

This warning appears when the GC would call into **JS** while tearing down an object, typically because:

* A **core vfunc** implemented in JS is invoked during GC (e.g. a method named like a GObject/GTK vfunc such as `get_flags`, `dispose`, `finalize`, `constructed`, etc.).
* A **signal or timeout** still references the object and fires during teardown, re-entering JS.
* Code emits signals or runs JS in `dispose`/`finalize`.

## Hard Rules

* **Do NOT implement core vfuncs in JS unless necessary.** In practice, only implement `vfunc_snapshot`, `vfunc_map/unmap`, and sometimes `vfunc_unroot`. Avoid implementing/defining methods that collide with existing vfunc names (e.g. `get_flags()`).
* **Rename any helper** that collides with vfunc names.

  * ❌ `get_flags()` → ✅ `getMyFlags()` (or `computeFlags()`).
    If you define `get_flags` as a method, GObject may treat it as a vfunc override and call it at unsafe times.
* **Never emit signals or schedule timeouts in `dispose`/`finalize`.**
* **Disconnect everything early.**

  * Connect in `vfunc_map()`.
  * Disconnect in `vfunc_unmap()` (and again in `vfunc_unroot()` as a safety net if the object can outlive mapping).

## Safe VFunc Set

* ✅ `vfunc_snapshot`, `vfunc_map`, `vfunc_unmap`, `vfunc_unroot`
* ⚠️ Only override `vfunc_dispose` to null-out external refs (no JS re-entry, no signals, no I/O)
* ❌ Avoid overriding: `get_flags`, `dispose`, `finalize`, `constructed`, `measure`, `size_allocate` (unless you know the pitfalls and keep them trivial/non-JS)

## Pattern: Guarded Signal Lifecycle

```typescript
export class MyWidget extends Gtk.Widget {
  private _signalIds: number[] = [];
  declare _button: Gtk.Button;

  vfunc_map(): void {
    super.vfunc_map();
    if (this._signalIds.length === 0) {
      this._signalIds.push(
        this._button.connect('clicked', () => this.emit('my-signal'))
      );
    }
  }

  vfunc_unmap(): void {
    for (const id of this._signalIds) this._button.disconnect(id);
    this._signalIds = [];
    super.vfunc_unmap();
  }

  vfunc_unroot(): void {
    // extra safety: disconnect anything global/singleton-related here
    super.vfunc_unroot();
  }

  // DO NOT define a method named `get_flags()` here — pick a different name.
  computeMyFlags(): number { /* ... */ return 0; }
}
```

## Pattern: Dispose without JS Re-entry

```typescript
vfunc_dispose(): void {
  // Only break external references; do not touch UI, do not emit signals,
  // do not call into other JS code that might run callbacks.
  // e.g., this._model = null;
  super.vfunc_dispose();
}
```

## Quick Fix Checklist for Your Error

* [ ] Search your codebase for **`get_flags(`** and **rename** to avoid vfunc collision.
* [ ] Ensure you do **not** implement other core vfuncs in JS unless required.
* [ ] Move all **signal connects** into `vfunc_map()`; **disconnect** in `vfunc_unmap()` (and `vfunc_unroot()` if needed).
* [ ] Remove any **JS work** (`emit`, async work, timeouts, I/O) from `dispose/finalize`.
* [ ] Verify no **timeouts/intervals** or **global signal connections** survive beyond `unmap/unroot`.

# Signal Management Best Practices

## Proper Signal Connection Lifecycle

* Connect signals in `vfunc_map()` (widget is visible/alive).
* Disconnect in `vfunc_unmap()` (widget no longer visible).
* Store handler IDs for cleanup; guard against double connections.

**Example**

```typescript
export class ManagedSignals extends Gtk.Widget {
  private _ids: number[] = [];
  declare _btn: Gtk.Button;

  vfunc_map(): void {
    super.vfunc_map();
    if (this._ids.length === 0) {
      this._ids.push(this._btn.connect('clicked', () => this.emit('clicked-once')));
    }
  }

  vfunc_unmap(): void {
    for (const id of this._ids) this._btn.disconnect(id);
    this._ids = [];
    super.vfunc_unmap();
  }
}
```

# Best Practices

* Keep classes single-purpose.
* Document properties and signals.
* Use strong typing (TypeScript + gjsify types).
* Test property bindings and signals.
* Use libadwaita for GNOME apps.
* Profile graphics when doing custom drawing.
* Prefer declarative bindings over imperative updates.
* Follow proper signal lifecycle patterns.
* Regularly check updated GTK & GJS docs.
